First step: Getting the data ready.

Visualise time series objects. What seems to be correlated?

Let’s check, if the series are stationary.

No, they are not. Let’s see, if we can achieve more stationarity by differencing the time series.

Looks like it! Let’s test that again with the correlogram.

It seems we have to fit an autoregressive distributed lag model, to account for the autocorrelation in the dependent variable.

Autoregressive distributed lag model

When correctly specified, this one works like a charm!

Choosing the right model for each country.

~For Spain, none of the models we tested, achieves a particularly good fit. Out of these moderately performing models, the first one has the better fit. However, because it is closely followed by the second model which is more coherent with our assumption that the changes in reproduction rate would follow changes in the policy stringency, we also choose the second model for our following analysis for Italy.~

As could be expected telling from the comparatively bad model fit, for Spain, the effect of policy stringency on the reproduction rate is not statistically significant at the p<=0.05-level. However, for Italy, Spain and France both the effect of the lagged dependent variable and the effect of the stringency index are significant and in line with our expectations, where increases in the policy stringency would lead to decreases in the reproduction rate. Interestingly, the estimates for the strength of the effect also lie very closely across the three countries, with Italy having a slightly stronger effect.

Let’s check, whether the error terms are autocorrelated.

Indeed, the error-terms are not correlated, except for two cases for Spain and France, where the autocorrelation for the error terms slightly exceeds the p <= 0.05 boundaries. However, this can be expected for 2 out of effectively 64 correlations tested.
